Definitions
Postures

Literal Posture: A user interface is presented to the Player from a Character’s point of view as part of the story. The Player is literally seeing through the Character’s eyes or hearing their thoughts.
+1


Metric Posture: A user interface is attached to the World or a local reference frame and enhances the Player’s spatial awareness of a Character’s surroundings.


Expressionist Posture: The user interface conveys an emotional state to the Player using visual properties of the display.


Formal Posture: The user interface represents game status, concepts, and utilities to the Player by fashioning a coded resemblance.

Reference Frames

Camera: Points in the World are projected into the bounds of a viewport. The Camera often behaves as a Character in its own right—controlled by the Player while being constrained by the World. Cameras have unique reference frames derived from the World.
+2


Screen: The World and its game entities are viewed by the Player as pixels (instead of objects) displayed on a 2-dimensional screen. Positions, rotations, and translations are considered in terms of (x,y) coordinates.
